[3] Singapore: imported
Date: Wed 22 Jun 2022
Source: The Straits Times [edited]
https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/spore-confirms-imported-case-of-monkeypox-13-close-contacts-identified


The Ministry of Health (MoH) has confirmed an imported case of monkeypox here. The patient is a 42 year old British man who works as a flight attendant and was in Singapore between last Wednesday and last Friday (15-17 Jun 2022) and again on Sunday [19 Jun 2022] as he flew in and out of the country, said the MoH on Tuesday night [21 Jun 2022].

He tested positive for monkeypox on Monday [20 Jun 2022] and is currently warded at the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID). His condition is stable, said the MoH, adding that contact tracing is ongoing. Thirteen close contacts had been identified as of Tuesday [21 Jun 2022]. All close contacts will be placed on quarantine for 21 days since their last contact with the patient. The 2 low-risk contacts have also been placed on phone surveillance, said the MoH.

Those under phone surveillance will receive daily phone calls during a 21-day period to monitor for any onset of symptoms. If they are suspected of being infected, they will immediately be taken to the NCID for further evaluation and isolation to prevent further transmission.

This is the 1st imported monkeypox infection detected in Singapore since 2019, when a Nigerian man tested positive. The MoH also said on [6 Jun 2022] that a traveller who transited through Singapore to Australia the week before had tested positive for monkeypox.

Giving more details about the latest imported case, the MoH said the man developed a headache on [14 Jun 2022] and a fever 2 days later [16 Jun 2022]. These symptoms subsequently resolved, but he then developed rashes on his skin on Sunday [19 Jun 2022]. He sought medical attention via teleconsultation that night and was taken to the NCID the next day [20 Jun 2022] for further assessment.

The MoH said contact tracing is ongoing for the affected flights and for the duration of his stay in Singapore. "During this period, he had largely remained in his hotel room, except to visit a massage establishment and eat at 3 food establishments on [16 Jun 2022].

"In general, the risk of transmission to visitors at these locations is low, as data has shown that monkeypox transmits through close physical or prolonged contact. All 4 locations visited by the case are undergoing cleaning and disinfection," said the ministry. It urged members of the public, especially travellers, to be vigilant and maintain a high standard of personal hygiene, including washing their hands frequently after going to the toilet or when their hands are soiled. The MoH [advised] that [people] should seek immediate medical attention if they develop any disease symptoms -- such as the sudden onset of high fever, swollen lymph nodes and rash -- that are compatible with monkeypox, and they should inform their doctor of their recent travel history.

[byline: Prisca Ang]

